- **`X-RateLimit-Reset` / `Retry-After`** are derived from when the *oldest* relevant timestamp ages out (`timestamps[0] + windowMs`), which is the actual moment capacity frees up — not an arbitrary interval edge.

A couple of notes for production:
- This is **in-memory and per-process**. Behind PM2 cluster mode or multiple Linode nodes, each worker keeps its own buckets, so the effective limit is `maxRequests × workers`. For a shared limit, back the store with Redis (sorted sets via `ZREMRANGEBYSCORE` map cleanly onto this same algorithm).
- Storing one timestamp per request costs `O(maxRequests)` memory per active IP. With very large `maxRequests`, consider a sliding-window-counter approximation instead.

