### How it works — step by step

| Step | Detail |
|------|--------|
| **Window** | Each IP owns an array of request timestamps. On every hit, timestamps older than `now − windowMs` are spliced from the front (O(stale) time, and stale entries are always contiguous at the front because we append in order). |
| **Decision** | If `remaining.length >= maxRequests` → 429. Otherwise, push `now` and call `next()`. |
| **Retry-After** | The earliest slot that will free up is `timestamps[0] + windowMs`. The gap from now to that moment (in whole seconds) is the `Retry-After` value. |
| **Reset header** | Same calculation: `⌈(timestamps[0] + windowMs) / 1000⌉` in epoch seconds, matching the RFC 6585 / IETF convention most API clients expect. |
| **Cleanup** | A `setInterval` every 60 s removes IPs whose last timestamp is already outside the window. `unref()` prevents this timer from blocking process exit. |

